README.md
     1ÔåÆ# Archived project. No maintenance. 
     3ÔåÆThis project is not maintained anymore and is archived. Feel free to fork and
     4ÔåÆmake your own changes if needed. For more detail read my blog post: [Taking an indefinite sabbatical from my projects](https://arslan.io/2018/10/09/taking-an-indefinite-sabbatical-from-my-projects/)
     5ÔåÆ
     6ÔåÆThanks to everyone for their valuable feedback and contributions.
     7ÔåÆ
     8ÔåÆ# Structs
    10ÔåÆStructs contains various utilities to work with Go (Golang) structs. It was
    11ÔåÆinitially used by me to convert a struct into a `map[string]interface{}`. With
    12ÔåÆtime I've added other utilities for structs.  It's basically a high level
    13ÔåÆpackage based on primitives from the reflect package. Feel free to add new
    14ÔåÆfunctions or improve the existing code.
    15ÔåÆ
    16ÔåÆ## Install
    18ÔåÆ```bash
    19ÔåÆgo get github.com/fatih/structs
    20ÔåÆ```
    21ÔåÆ
    22ÔåÆ## Usage and Examples
    24ÔåÆJust like the standard lib `strings`, `bytes` and co packages, `structs` has
    25ÔåÆmany global functions to manipulate or organize your struct data. Lets define
    26ÔåÆand declare a struct:
    27ÔåÆ
    28ÔåÆ```go
    29ÔåÆtype Server struct {
    30ÔåÆ	Name        string `json:"name,omitempty"`
    31ÔåÆ	ID          int
    32ÔåÆ	Enabled     bool
    33ÔåÆ	users       []string // not exported
    34ÔåÆ	http.Server          // embedded
    35ÔåÆ}
    36ÔåÆ
    37ÔåÆserver := &Server{
    38ÔåÆ	Name:    "gopher",
    39ÔåÆ	ID:      123456,
    40ÔåÆ	Enabled: true,
    41ÔåÆ}
    42ÔåÆ```
    43ÔåÆ
    44ÔåÆ```go
    45ÔåÆ// Convert a struct to a map[string]interface{}
    46ÔåÆ// => {"Name":"gopher", "ID":123456, "Enabled":true}
    47ÔåÆm := structs.Map(server)
    48ÔåÆ
    49ÔåÆ// Convert the values of a struct to a []interface{}
    50ÔåÆ// => ["gopher", 123456, true]
    51ÔåÆv := structs.Values(server)
    52ÔåÆ
    53ÔåÆ// Convert the names of a struct to a []string
    54ÔåÆ// (see "Names methods" for more info about fields)
    55ÔåÆn := structs.Names(server)
    56ÔåÆ
    57ÔåÆ// Convert the values of a struct to a []*Field
    58ÔåÆ// (see "Field methods" for more info about fields)
    59ÔåÆf := structs.Fields(server)
    60ÔåÆ
    61ÔåÆ// Return the struct name => "Server"
    62ÔåÆn := structs.Name(server)
    63ÔåÆ
    64ÔåÆ// Check if any field of a struct is initialized or not.
    65ÔåÆh := structs.HasZero(server)
    66ÔåÆ
    67ÔåÆ// Check if all fields of a struct is initialized or not.
    68ÔåÆz := structs.IsZero(server)
    69ÔåÆ
    70ÔåÆ// Check if server is a struct or a pointer to struct
    71ÔåÆi := structs.IsStruct(server)
    72ÔåÆ```
    73ÔåÆ
    74ÔåÆ### Struct methods
    76ÔåÆThe structs functions can be also used as independent methods by creating a new
    77ÔåÆ`*structs.Struct`. This is handy if you want to have more control over the
    78ÔåÆstructs (such as retrieving a single Field).
    79ÔåÆ
    80ÔåÆ```go
    81ÔåÆ// Create a new struct type:
    82ÔåÆs := structs.New(server)
    83ÔåÆ
    84ÔåÆm := s.Map()              // Get a map[string]interface{}
    85ÔåÆv := s.Values()           // Get a []interface{}
    86ÔåÆf := s.Fields()           // Get a []*Field
    87ÔåÆn := s.Names()            // Get a []string
    88ÔåÆf := s.Field(name)        // Get a *Field based on the given field name
    89ÔåÆf, ok := s.FieldOk(name)  // Get a *Field based on the given field name
    90ÔåÆn := s.Name()             // Get the struct name
    91ÔåÆh := s.HasZero()          // Check if any field is uninitialized
    92ÔåÆz := s.IsZero()           // Check if all fields are uninitialized
    93ÔåÆ```
    94ÔåÆ
    95ÔåÆ### Field methods
    97ÔåÆWe can easily examine a single Field for more detail. Below you can see how we
    98ÔåÆget and interact with various field methods:
    99ÔåÆ
   100ÔåÆ
   101ÔåÆ```go
   102ÔåÆs := structs.New(server)
   103ÔåÆ
   104ÔåÆ// Get the Field struct for the "Name" field
   105ÔåÆname := s.Field("Name")
   106ÔåÆ
   107ÔåÆ// Get the underlying value,  value => "gopher"
   108ÔåÆvalue := name.Value().(string)
   109ÔåÆ
   110ÔåÆ// Set the field's value
   111ÔåÆname.Set("another gopher")
   112ÔåÆ
   113ÔåÆ// Get the field's kind, kind =>  "string"
   114ÔåÆname.Kind()
   115ÔåÆ
   116ÔåÆ// Check if the field is exported or not
   117ÔåÆif name.IsExported() {
   118ÔåÆ	fmt.Println("Name field is exported")
   119ÔåÆ}
   120ÔåÆ
   121ÔåÆ// Check if the value is a zero value, such as "" for string, 0 for int
   122ÔåÆif !name.IsZero() {
   123ÔåÆ	fmt.Println("Name is initialized")
   124ÔåÆ}
   125ÔåÆ
   126ÔåÆ// Check if the field is an anonymous (embedded) field
   127ÔåÆif !name.IsEmbedded() {
   128ÔåÆ	fmt.Println("Name is not an embedded field")
   129ÔåÆ}
   130ÔåÆ
   131ÔåÆ// Get the Field's tag value for tag name "json", tag value => "name,omitempty"
   132ÔåÆtagValue := name.Tag("json")
   133ÔåÆ```
   134ÔåÆ
   135ÔåÆNested structs are supported too:
   136ÔåÆ
   137ÔåÆ```go
   138ÔåÆaddrField := s.Field("Server").Field("Addr")
   139ÔåÆ
   140ÔåÆ// Get the value for addr
   141ÔåÆa := addrField.Value().(string)
   142ÔåÆ
   143ÔåÆ// Or get all fields
   144ÔåÆhttpServer := s.Field("Server").Fields()
   145ÔåÆ```
   146ÔåÆ
   147ÔåÆWe can also get a slice of Fields from the Struct type to iterate over all
   148ÔåÆfields. This is handy if you wish to examine all fields:
   149ÔåÆ
   150ÔåÆ```go
   151ÔåÆs := structs.New(server)
   152ÔåÆ
   153ÔåÆfor _, f := range s.Fields() {
   154ÔåÆ	fmt.Printf("field name: %+v\n", f.Name())
   155ÔåÆ
   156ÔåÆ	if f.IsExported() {
   157ÔåÆ		fmt.Printf("value   : %+v\n", f.Value())
   158ÔåÆ		fmt.Printf("is zero : %+v\n", f.IsZero())
   159ÔåÆ	}
   160ÔåÆ}
   161ÔåÆ```
   162ÔåÆ
